            <p>Isaac Brandon.			David H. Brandon.			Nathaniel Brandon.<lb/></p>
            <p>Isaac Brandon &#38; Bro&#39;s.<lb/>
                New York Panama &#38; Colon.<lb/>							
                Cable Address.<lb/>							
                &#34;Gritz&#59;&#34; Newyork.<lb/></p>
            <p>35 Broadway<lb/>
                New York&#44; November 10<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1889<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr Morais<lb/>
                Philadelphia.<lb/></p>
            <p>Reverend Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I presume to trouble you on the<lb/> strength of the enclosed kind lines of Dr Mendes<lb/> &#38; to assure you of my appreciation should you<lb/> be able to render the service I solicit<lb/></p>
            <p>A. Mr J M Belisario for many<lb/> years&#44; an inmate of the &#34;Penn Hospital for the Insane&#44;<lb/> 49<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St Market &#38; Haverford Av&#41; is so seriously ill that<lb/> there is reason to expect his early demise.<lb/></p>
            <p>As the unfortunate has neither<lb/> relatives nor friends in your city to see to the<lb/> last services according to the rites of his religion<lb/> I hope you will consent to perform the sad duty<lb/> by charging an undertaker with the necessary arrangements<lb/> &#38; adopting such measures as may be requisite to<lb/> ensure a strictly orthodox ceremony.<lb/></p>
            <p>If you will drop me a line at<lb/> an early date you will allow my making arrangements<lb/> for your time notification by the Institution &#38; oblige<lb/> Rev. Sir Very respectfully Yours<lb/> D H Brandon<lb/></p>
            </body>
